\chapter{The command-line interface}

The official Zulip CLI tools---[[zulip-api]] and [[zulip-send]]---cover
message sending and a handful of administrative operations, but lack
basic discovery commands.
When we need to send a direct message with [[zulip-send]], we must
already know the recipient's email address; there is no built-in way to
look it up.
Similarly, there is no command to list the available streams (channels),
inspect the topics inside a stream, or read a stream's history from the
terminal.

The [[zulipcli]] command fills these gaps with five subcommands:
\begin{description}
\item[users] List users, optionally filtered by a name or email
  pattern.
\item[send] Send a message to a stream or directly to a user.
\item[streams] List available streams.
\item[topics] List the topics inside a stream.
\item[read] Read the history of a stream or one topic within it.
\end{description}

We keep the subcommand pattern familiar from Git and the
[[canvaslms]] tool, but implement it with [[Typer]] instead of
[[argparse]]. Typer still lets each subcommand read like an ordinary
Python function, while adding shell completion for command names,
option names, and argument values.


